But the way was much more difficult than it had been in the ascent‚ the declivity on the Italian side of the Alps being in most places shorter, and consequently more perpendicular3 while the whole way was nar- row and slippery, so that the soldiers could not pre- vent their feet from sliding, nor, if they made the least false step, could they, on falling, stop themselves: and thus men and beasts tumbled promiscuously over one another.
